<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-formulae-and-variations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Formulae and Variations</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>In our study of mathematics so far, we have used <strong>formulae</strong> as shorthand rules to describe relationships between quantities. For example, the formula for the area of a rectangle, <m>A = L \times W</m>, tells us exactly how the area changes if we alter the length or width. In the real world, quantities are rarely static; they often <em>vary</em> in response to one another.</p>
    <p><strong>Variation</strong> is the study of these dynamic relationships. It allows us to move beyond calculating a single value and towards understanding the <em>behaviour</em> of a system. By using variation, we can answer questions such as:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>How much more fuel will a car consume if its speed is doubled?</li>
      <li>How does the intensity of light change as you move further away from a lamp?</li>
      <li>How many more workers are needed to complete a construction project in half the time?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The two pillars of this chapter are:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Formulae</strong>: We will learn how to make a specific variable the subject of an equation, allowing us to solve for any unknown quantity within a complex relationship. This is the art of <strong>transposition</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Variations</strong>: We will explore the different ways variables interact:</li>
    </ol>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Direct Variation</strong>: One quantity grows as the other grows, <m>y = kx</m>.</li>
      <li><strong>Inverse Variation</strong>: One quantity grows while the other shrinks, <m>y = \frac{k}{x}</m>.</li>
      <li><strong>Joint and Partial Variation</strong>: A quantity depends on multiple factors or a combination of fixed and changing costs.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Understanding formulae and variations is the key to mathematical modelling. Whether you are an engineer calculating the load a bridge can carry or a business owner predicting profits, these tools allow you to predict the future based on the patterns of the present.</p>

  </introduction>

